title: Consultation with Matthew Goldberg
info:
3 aspects/roles = financial, realtor and title

* matthew's company - "correspondent lender", selects from a pool of investors/lendors that will finance the loan
* can't select bank
* may request the servicer though (if you know a good one)
* loans typiclly change hands quickly, should not affect the loan itself at all
	- initial packagers typically only want to hold a particular number of loans on portfolio

scenario 1: sell home and buy new home
	* simultaneous close, contingency
	* 500k, use 125k (25%) of the equity for downpayment, 375 loan , 50k in pocket, spitballed around 2500 month
	* for each 10k in loan amount, you'll look at approx. 55 bucks in monthly payment

scenario 2: sell home, pay portion/sum of loan, buy new home

scenario 3: rent home, buy another home
	* take equity loan out for some amount, used to buy new house; he gave a calc of 109k equity
	* can use portion of income to supplement everything
	* matt's company does NOT do heloc products (home equity line of credit)


5500-1500-300-420

3500/month in available additional debt

* "recast of the ammortization of a home", just a term for familiarity
* shrodinger's cat = a term to describe the concept/paradox of locking in a rate?
* tossed idea around of using one or other or both on loan based upon individual debts
* tri-merge credit check (checking all 3 bureaus)
* credit reports good for 4 months

title: Home buying consultation with Matthew Goldberg
info:
##questions
* what banks/rates are an option > if you finance through them, they are the only option
* can I use my bank > no
* is now a good time to sell > no straight answer
* when is a good time to buy > no straight answer
* what's the advice on renting existing home and picking up a second is it worth it in the long run > depends upon long-term goals
* how would we go about renting (LLC, incorporation, etc..) > need to consult realtor
* what's advice on selling now, renting till market 'bombs', thenbuying (taxes, penalties, etc...) > no real feedback
* what is your fee > it's baked into the interest rate, this guys is only part of the finance component; Rodney Coty says he'll do it for 5%, as long as we buy and sell through him
* how do we take some of the equity out for another debt (school loans) > do it after the house sells
* what are the taxes on the equity, how do we avoid the brunt, avoideffectively, etc... > no real feedback

##wish list
* brick/block construction
* 2500 sq/ft, larger kitchen and bathrooms
* car coverage (not necessarily garage)
* back yard space
* not adjacent to high-freq roads
* madison district
* irrigation
* pool

title: Mortgage notes
info:
* don't do heloc (home equity line of credit), don't use your house as a piggy bank
* do not take on a loan requiring PMI (primary mortgage insurance); it's supper expensive, lasts life of the loan, avoided by making sufficient down payment (20%)
* shop products like 15 and 20-year loans because you gain equity MUCH faster, they're worth it
* there's something called a 'wealth-builder' loan, where down payment is less?? not sure if only for first time buyers, etc... heard it on NPR

things to bring
- deck of cards
- more socks, one pair a day at least

things not to bring
- board games (just bring cards), too much space, not used
- video game systems, excess, can do it at home
- more than one tent
- excess beverages
- excess food (no more than 1 or 2 meals a day, since frequent eating out
- big cooler wasn't too useful for the amount of space it took, just need one good smaller cooler (soft coolers leak when ice used, ice packs ok)

things to remember
- don't bring too many clothes, if long trip then at least one wash will be necessary
- don't do more than two places, got sick of packing up the car each time
- think about flying, save a day of vacation time?  traffic in L.A. area very time consuming
- get better lodging, quality time, rather than cheap
- space in oceanside a pain, couch in bedroom negated comfort, vanity useless
- think about better luggage (each having large/touch box better than several soft duffel type bags)

title: Suit shopping
info:
...for Ally Califano's birthday party and funeral for Regina's Uncle

According to the salesman at Men's Warhouse:
* jacket sizes based upon chest measurement along with length of coat (i.e. 44S, or 50L, or 48R)
* coat lengths are S short R regular or L long
* typically the button is only latched during introduction or during formal times (ceremonies)
* there doesn't need to be great range of motion during formal times, else just unbutton
* when the jacket matches the pants, it's a suit, else it's a sport coat
* suits that are 'separate' allow for more customized size
* suits that come with pants include the jacket at some size, and the pants at 6 sizes less (i.e. coat at 46 chest and then pants at 40 waist)
* suits are generally made to be adjustable
* 'executive' style jackets allow more room in the gut area (for fattys)

What fit me nice today was:
46R jacket and 38 pants
shirt measurements are 32-33 arm length and 17 neck (also depends greatly upon the manufacturer)

title: Removed splint from ankle
info:
* went in for follow up appointment on my ankle, a post-operation review
* splint was removed and received an x-ray
* bone fragments on sides of foot visibly removed
* bone marrow was  taken from certian places in local area and spreak/smeared onto places where it was worn

* opted for the best possible result so she put me in a cast for 2 additional weeks, after which I should start therapy
